close_symbols: compile-time config macros that enable/disable pointer checks (e.g. OSAL_ERROR_CHECKING)
explanation: OS_CHECK_POINTER — This macro is invoked twice in the function. Its expansion determines whether those lines perform meaningful operations (e.g. null checks that return an error, logging, assertions) or are compiled away; knowing its definition is essential to decide if those operations are dead code. OS_ObjectIdFindByName — The function assigned to return_code; its semantics and side effects (what it reads/writes, its possible return values) are needed to determine if the call (and the subsequent return) affects program behaviour. LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE — The constant passed into OS_ObjectIdFindByName; its value/type can change OS_ObjectIdFindByName behaviour and therefore whether the call is meaningful. OS_printf — Frequently used inside pointer-check macros to report errors; printing is a behavioural side effect (timing/IO). If OS_CHECK_POINTER invokes OS_printf, removing that call would change behaviour. osal_id_t — The pointer type checked/used by the macro and passed to OS_ObjectIdFindByName; its definition (pointer vs. typedefed integer, constness, side-effects on dereference) is needed to judge whether operations on it are meaningful. int32 — The return type used for return_code and function return; knowing the exact integer type and any associated error-code conventions helps interpret return values as meaningful behaviour. OS_SUCCESS, OS_INVALID_POINTER (or equivalent return-code constants) — The specific return-code values used by OS_CHECK_POINTER and OS_ObjectIdFindByName are needed to know whether branches/assignments can influence observable behaviour. compile-time config macros that enable/disable pointer checks (e.g. OSAL_ERROR_CHECKING) — If pointer-checks are conditional on build configuration, the macro calls may be compiled out in some builds; this directly affects whether the OS_CHECK_POINTER expansions are dead code in a given build.
